{"title_page": "North Hollywood High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n|name              = North Hollywood High School\n|image             = NHHS Kennedy Hall.jpg\n|imagesize         = \n|streetaddress     = 5231 Colfax Avenue\n|city              = [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|North Hollywood]]\n|state             = [[California]]\n|zipcode           = 91601\n|country           = [[United States]]\n|coordinates       = {{coord|34|09|57|N|118|23|20|W|type:edu_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|pushpin_map = United States San Fernando Valley#United States Los Angeles Metropolitan Area#USA California#United States\n|schooltype        = [[high school]]\n|type              = [[Public high school|Public]]\n|established       = 1927\n|status            = Open\n|district          = [[Los Angeles Unified School District]]\n|superintendent    = [[Austin Beutner]]\n|principal         = Ricardo Rosales\n|faculty           = 118\n|grades            = [[Ninth grade|9]]-[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n|age range         = 14-18\n|enrollment        = 2,501 (2018)<ref>https://www.ed-data.org/school/Los-Angeles/Los-Angeles-Unified/North-Hollywood-Senior-High</ref>\n|grade9            = 749\n|grade10           = 649\n|grade11           = 537\n|grade12           = 566\n|ratio             = 21:1\n|language          = [[English language|English]]\n|hours_in_day      = 7 hours 16 minutes (Monday, Wednesday-Friday)<br />6 hours 10 minutes (Tuesday)\n|campus            = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|colors            = {{Color box|blue|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|gray|border=darkgray}} Blue, White, Gray\n|song              = Huskies Are We\n|conference        = East Valley League<br>CIF Los Angeles City Section\n|mascot            = Huskies\n|nickname          = Huskies, Big Blue\n|rival             = [[Polytechnic High School (Los Angeles)|Polytechnic High School]]<br />[[Grant High School (Los Angeles)|Ulysses S. Grant High School]]\n|SAT               = 485 Reading<br />481 Math<br />482 Writing<br />1448 Average (2016)\n|ACT               = 23 Reading<br />22 Math<br />22 English<br />21 Science<br />22 Average (2016)\n|newspaper         = The Arcade\n|feeders           = [[Walter Reed Middle School]]<br>Sun Valley Middle School<br>Roy Romer Middle School<br>Gaspar de Portola Middle School\n|homepage          = [http://nhhs.net/ NHHS]<br>[http://highlygiftedmagnet.org/ NHHS HGM]<br>[http://zoomagnet.org/ NHHS Zoo Magnet]<br>[http://royalregiment.org/ NHHS Music]\n| module        = {{Infobox mapframe\n| stroke-color = #C60C30\n| stroke-width  = 3\n| marker        = school\n| marker-color = #1F2F57\n| zoom          = 13}}\n}}\n\n'''North Hollywood High School''' is a [[public high school]] in [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|North Hollywood]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]. NHHS is located in the [[San Fernando Valley]] and enrolls approximately 2,500 students each year. Several neighborhoods, including most of [[North Hollywood, California|North Hollywood]], [[Valley Village, Los Angeles, California|Valley Village]], [[Studio City, Los Angeles, California|Studio City]] and [[Sun Valley, Los Angeles, California|Sun Valley]], send students to this school. As of 2019, NHHS is accredited by the [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]. As of 2019, the [[school principal]] is Mr. Ricardo Rosales.\n\n==Facilities==\nThe campus facilities include three main buildings (Kennedy Hall, Frasher Hall, and Randolph Hall), an agricultural area with livestock, a garden, an auditorium, a cafeteria, two gymnasiums, multiple computer labs with internet access, an auto mechanic shop, a wood shop, an instrumental music room, a football field, two softball fields, a baseball diamond, two tennis court areas, a teachers' parking lot, an art room, a college center, a parent center, a student store, and a library.\n\n==History==\n[[File:NHHS Student Quad.jpg|thumb|''The student quad.'']]\nBuilt in 1927, '''Lankershim High School''' was named for the town of Lankershim (first called Toluca, now North Hollywood) and its founding family. It opened with only a main building, auditorium, gymnasium, and a shop & mechanics building, with 800 students, graduating its first class in 1928. The Board of Education was asked to employ teachers who were already residents of North Hollywood, creating jobs and education opportunities right in the area. Lankershim High School was renamed '''North Hollywood High School''' in 1929. In 1937, a girls' gymnasium and a second major classroom building, now named Frasher Hall after former principal Roscoe Frasher, were built. In 1950, the third major classroom building, now named Randolph Hall, was built. In the 1950s, many smaller construction projects took place, including the agricultural classrooms, the boys' gymnasium, the home-side bleachers, and the instrumental music room. In 1965, the main hall was named the [[John F. Kennedy]] Memorial Hall after the slain President. In 1966, the cafeteria, student store, and two shop buildings were built. In 1973, the Amelia Earhart Continuation High School was built on the campus' Northeast corner. In the late 1990s, thirteen modular buildings were installed to support an increase in the number of students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/16/news/mn-20297/3|title=L.A. Unified May Need High Schools to Go Year-Round|first1=DOUG|last1=SMITH|first2=KRISTINA|last2=SAUERWEIN|date=16 April 2000|website=Articles.latimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===1990s and beyond===\nIn 1996, the LAUSD board voted to move NHHS to a [[year-round school|year-round schedule]], but after more classroom space was found, the board reversed course. Several NHHS parents and community members did not want a year-round schedule since they feared it would negatively impact the [[Highly Gifted Magnet]].<ref name=Sauerweinmaythreaten>Sauerwein, Kristina. \"[https://articles.latimes.com/1999/sep/30/local/me-16638 Enrollment May Threaten Program for Highly Gifted].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. September 30, 1999. Retrieved on January 9, 2016.</ref> According to the 1996 scheduling magnet students were supposed to get July\u2013May, which would have impacted their ability to attend summer programs operated by [[Ivy League]] universities. The zoo magnet students were to get the September\u2013June schedule.<ref>Folmar, Kate. \"[https://articles.latimes.com/1996-03-02/local/me-42077_1_north-hollywood North Hollywood : High School to Review Its Magnet Scheduling].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. March 2, 1996. Retrieved on January 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2000, [[Ramon C. Cortines]], the LAUSD superintendent, stated that the overcrowding at NHHS was more severe than originally anticipated,<ref>Sauerwein, Kristina. \"[https://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/06/local/me-16675 Cortines Deals Blow to High School Schedule Fight].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. April 6, 2000. Retrieved on January 9, 2016.</ref> and he announced that NHHS was going year-round. This was despite parents and students protesting against the move for several months.<ref>Sauerwein, Kristina. \"[https://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/08/local/me-17333 New N. Hollywood High Schedule Incites Anger].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. April 8, 2000. Retrieved on January 9, 2016.</ref> From 2000 to 2007, NHHS was a year-round school with three tracks.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/08/local/me-17330 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Kristina | last=Sauerwein | title=North Hollywood High to Begin Year-Round Calendar | date=2000-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, [[East Valley High School (Los Angeles)|East Valley High School]] opened, relieving overcrowding at NHHS.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/04/local/me-schools4 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Howard | last=Blume | title=School Spirit Is Given a Boost in the Valley | date=2006-10-04}}</ref> In 2007, the traditional calendar was re-adopted and the students were divided into many [[Small Learning Communities]] (SLCs).  All but three of these SLCs were closed in June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/planlausd/surveys/V-2%20%207%20Schools/VERSION%202-%20North%20Hollywood%20HS.pdf|title=North Hollywood High School: Campus Pre-Planning Survey|website=Laschools.org|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, it was announced that NHHS was selected to undergo major renovations, including upgrading buildings and removing portable buildings, to be completed in five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patch.com/california/northhollywood/north-hollywood-high-school-be-fast-tracked-major-rennovations|title=North Hollywood High School to Be Fast-Tracked for Major Rennovations(sic)|date=28 January 2015|website=Patch.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 there was a proposal to co-locate a charter school, Valley International Preparatory High School (VIPHS), on the NHHS campus, but there was student opposition; students created an online petition to oppose the co-location.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2018/03/03/north-hollywood-high-may-have-to-share-its-campus-with-a-charter-school-and-some-students-arent-happy-about-it/|title=North Hollywood High may have to share its campus with a charter school, and these students aren't happy about it|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|date=2018-03-03|accessdate=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nNHHS contains three [[magnet school|magnet programs]]; the [[Highly Gifted Magnet]] (HGM), the Zoo Magnet, and the STEM Magnet. There are also three [[Small Learning Communities]] (SLCs); the Humanitas School for Advanced Studies, the Home Engineering Academy, and the Freshmen Academy.\n\n===Highly Gifted Magnet===\nThe [[Highly Gifted Magnet]] was established in 1989, and is a component of the voluntary integration program of the LAUSD, designed to provide an academically challenging college preparatory program. The program is designed to prepare its students to thrive in the most demanding of university environments. The students in the HGM are from all over Los Angeles, and have a variety of extracurricular interests, as well as diversity in their academic directions.\n\nChildren are eligible if they test in the 99.5th percentile or above on an intelligence test conducted by an LAUSD psychologist. Priority is given to children with 99.9%, officially \u201cHighly Gifted\u201d by LAUSD definition. If there are openings remaining in the program, \u201cGifted\u201d students with 99.5%-99.8% may be admitted with priority based on magnet points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highlygiftedmagnet.org/how-to-apply/|title=Eligibility & Admissions|website=The Highly Gifted Magnet}}</ref> The program had 265 students,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highlygiftedmagnet.org/about/|title=About the HGM|website=The Highly Gifted Magnet}}</ref> 4 administrators, and 7 faculty members in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highlygiftedmagnet.org/faculty/|title=Contact Faculty & Admin|website=The Highly Gifted Magnet}}</ref>\n\n===Zoo Magnet===\n[[File:NHHS Cafeteria.jpg|thumb|''The student cafeteria.'']]\nThe Zoo Magnet was established in 1981, and is a specialized school that buses students to a small campus next to the [[Los Angeles Zoo]] in [[Griffith Park]]. At this site, approximately 300 students take standard classes such as history, math, and English, in addition to [[Advanced Placement]] classes related to biological and [[zoology|zoological sciences]]. Many of these classes include fieldwork in the [[Los Angeles Zoo|Los Angeles Zoo and Botanical Gardens]], [[Los Angeles River]] ecosystem, [[Autry National Center]] and the natural world of [[Griffith Park]] for tours and observation. Classes are on a block schedule, meeting three days a week for two hours per class.\n\n===STEM Magnet===\nThe STEM Magnet was established in 2018, and is an alternative course of study that prepares students for college and career opportunities in Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math.\n\n===Small Learning Communities===\nThe [[Small Learning Communities]] (SLCs) are intended to increase student achievement by personalizing the educational experience of students in large schools. Of the eight SLCs originally created, three remain as of 2019; the Humanitas School for Advanced Studies (HSAS), the Home Engineering Academy (HEA), and the Freshmen Academy (FA). The HSAS is designed for identified gifted, high achieving, high-ability students who show an interest in taking Honors and [[Advanced Placement]] courses. The HEA specializes in the construction and building trades.\n\n===Rankings===\nIn 2020, [[Niche (company)|Niche]] designated NHHS as #279 in the country, and was awarded an overall grade of \"A\", with an A- in Academics, an A- in Diversity, an A in Teachers, an A in College Prep, a B- in Clubs and Activities, a B in Health and Safety, a B in Administration, a C+ in Sports, a C in Food, and a C in Resources and Facilities.<ref>https://www.niche.com/k12/north-hollywood-senior-high-school-north-hollywood-ca/rankings/</ref>\n\nIn 2020, ''[[Newsweek]]'' ranked NHHS as #2183 in the country for STEM programs, with a score of 63.6/100.<ref>https://www.newsweek.com/americas-best-stem-high-schools-2020/best-stem-schools-2001-2500</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked NHHS as 1,558th in the country, 233rdd of all high schools in California, 98th in Los Angeles, and gave it a College Readiness Index of 39/100. It also ranked the Highly Gifted Magnet as 192nd in the country.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/california/districts/los-angeles-unified-school-district/north-hollywood-senior-high-2573</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the [[California Standardized Testing and Reporting Program|California Assessment of Student Performance and Progress]] evaluated 11th grade students in English and Mathematics. In the area of English, 11th grade students were classified as 15% standard not met, 17% standard nearly met, 32% standard met, and 36% stanard exceeded. In the area of Math, 11th grade students were classified as 37% standard not met, 26% standard nearly met, 17% standard met, and 20% standard exceeded.<ref>https://caaspp.cde.ca.gov/sb2018/ViewReport?ps=true&lstTestYear=2018&lstTestType=B&lstGroup=1&lstCounty=19&lstDistrict=64733-000&lstSchool=1936350</ref>\n\nIn 2018, schooldigger.com ranked NHHS as 416th of all high schools in California, 25th of all high schools in LAUSD, and 2nd of all public/non-magnet high schools in LAUSD.<ref>https://www.schooldigger.com/go/CA/schools/2271003230/school.aspx</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the ''[[Washington Post]]'' ranked NHHS as 624th in the country, 77th of all high schools in California, 58th of all public high schools in California, 21st of all high schools in Los Angeles County, 11th of all high schools in LAUSD, and 1st of all high schools in District 2.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/local/high-school-challenge-2017/|title=U.S. high school rankings by state \u2014 Most challenging schools|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2017-18 school year, the average [[ACT Test]] scores were a 25 in Reading, a 25 in English, a 24 in Math, and a 24 in Science, each out of 36 points.<ref>https://data1.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/satactap/CollegeTest?cdscode=19647331936350&CollegeTest=act&year=2017-18</ref>\n\nIn 2016, LAUSD's new School Quality Improvement Index<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home.lausd.net/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=227154&type=d&pREC_ID=657699 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205212658/http://home.lausd.net/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=227154&type=d&pREC_ID=657699 |archivedate=2016-02-05 }} </ref> scored NHHS's 2014-15 year as 80/100, broken down into 10.51/15 in Academic Performance English Language Arts (64% met or exceeded standards), 12.01/15 in Academic Performance Math (37% met or exceeded standards), 11.25/20 in Four Year Cohort Graduation Rate (85% graduated class of 2014), 3.7/5 in Five Year Cohort Graduation Rate (90% graduated class of 2013), 3.51/5 in Six Year Cohort Graduation Rate (89% graduated class of 2012), 12.68/13.33 in Chronic Absenteeism (6% chronically absent), 13.35/13.33 in Suspension Rates (0% suspended/expelled), and 13.33/13.33 in English Learner Re-Designation (21% re-designated).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatschools.org/catalog/CORE_districts/LAUSD-NE/Abridged/North_Hollywood_Senior_High-19647331936350-hs.pdf|title=NORTH HOLLYWOOD SENIOR HIGH|date=28 March 2016|website=Greatschools.org|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave NHHS a grade of \"A\" in arts education, ranking it 6th of all secondary schools, and 9th of all schools within LAUSD. Out of over 700 schools, only 35 received an \"A\" grade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://schools.latimes.com/grading-the-arts/north-hollywood-senior-high-secondary/|title=North Hollywood Senior High|work=schools.latimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, ''[[Los Angeles Magazine]]'' ranked NHHS 14th in [[Los Angeles County]], 7th of all public schools in the county, 4th of all LAUSD schools, and 1st in District 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lamag.com/best-high-schools/75-los-angeles-county-high-schools-public-private-bring-best-students/|title=75 Los Angeles County High Schools\u2014Public and Private\u2014That Bring Out the Best in Students|work=Los Angeles Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, NHHS's [[Academic Performance Index (California public schools)|Academic Performance Index]] (API) score was 778, which is 22 points below the state goal, but an improvement of 8 points since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ed-data.org/school/Los-Angeles/Los-Angeles-Unified/North-Hollywood-Senior-High|title=EdData - School Profile - North Hollywood Senior High|work=ed-data.org}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2013-14 school year, the average [[SAT Reasoning Test]] score was 1557 of a possible 2400 points.<ref name=\"dq.cde.ca.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/satactap/sat.aspx?cyear=2013-14&cchoice=SAT4b&year=1314&cdscode=19647331936350&clevel=School&ctopic=sat&level=School|title=SAT Report (CA Dept of Education)|website=Dq.cde.ca.gov}}</ref>\n \nFor the 2013-14 school year, the [[CAHSEE|California High School Exit Exam]] (CAHSEE) classified 84% of 10th graders in English and 83% of 10th graders in Mathematics, as \"proficient or better.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ed-data.org/school/Los-Angeles/Los-Angeles-Unified/North-Hollywood-Senior-High|title=EdData - School Profile - North Hollywood Senior High|website=Ed-data.org}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2014-15 school year, in the Physical Fitness Exam for 9th graders, 89.8% of students in Abdominal Strength, 65.5% of students in Aerobic Capacity, 63.1% of students in Body Composition, 91.2% of students in Flexibility, 92.1% of students in Trunk Extension Strength, and 80.9% of students in Upper Body Strength, were considered to be in the \"Healthy Fitness Zone.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/PhysFitness/PFTDN/Summary2011.aspx?r=0&t=1&y=2014-15&c=19647331936350&n=0000|title=Physical Fitness Test Results (CA Dept of Education)|website=Dq.cde.ca.gov}}</ref>\n\n===Advanced Placement Courses===\nNHHS offers 25 [[Advanced Placement]] courses: [[AP Biology]], [[AP Calculus AB]], [[AP Calculus BC]], [[AP Chemistry]], [[AP Computer Science A]], [[AP Computer Science Principles]], [[AP English Language and Composition]], [[AP English Literature and Composition]], [[AP Environmental Science]], [[AP European History]], [[AP French Language]], [[AP Human Geography]], [[AP Macroeconomics]], [[AP Music Theory]], [[AP Physics 2]], [[AP Physics C: Electricity and Magnetism]], [[AP Physics C: Mechanics]], [[AP Psychology]], [[AP Spanish Language]], [[AP Spanish Literature]], [[AP Statistics]], [[AP Studio Art]], [[AP US Government and Politics]], [[AP US History]], and [[AP World History]].\n\nFor the 2017-18 school year, 820 students took 1,883 AP examinations, with 20% receiving a score of 1, 24% receiving a score of 2, 22% receiving a score of 3, 16% receiving a score of 4, and 18% receiving a score of 5.<ref>https://data1.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/satactap/CollegeTest?cdscode=19647331936350&CollegeTest=ap&year=2017-18</ref>\n\n== Extracurriculars ==\nThere are a wide variety of extracurricular activities offered at NHHS. While many of these activities are provided by the school, after-school partnerships exist with [[Los Angeles Valley College]] (LAVC) and L.A.C.E.R. Afterschool Programs.\n\n===Competitive Academics===\n[[File:NHHS Computer Lab.jpg|thumb|''One of the computer labs.'']]\n[[File:NHHS Library.jpg|thumb|''The library.'']]\n[[File:NHHS Woodshop.jpg|thumb|''The woodshop.'']]\nNHHS offers many highly successful teams in competitive academics:\n[[Academic Decathlon]],\n[[CyberPatriot]],\n[[DECA (organization)|DECA]],\n[[Moot Court|Duke Moot Court]],\n[[FIRST Robotics]],\n[[National FFA Organization|Future Farmers of America]],\n[[Mock Trial]],\n[[North American Computational Linguistics Open Competition|North American Computational Linguistics Open competition]],\n[[National Ocean Sciences Bowl]],\n[[Physics Olympiad]],\n[[Science Bowl]],\n[[Science Olympiad]], and\n[[Debate|Speech and Debate]].\n\n===Athletics===\n[[File:NHHS Boys' Gym.jpg|thumb|''The Boys' Gym.'']]\nThe NHHS Huskies compete in the [[CIF Los Angeles City Section]]'s East Valley League. NHHS's rivals are [[Polytechnic High School (Los Angeles)|Polytechnic High School]] and [[Grant High School (Los Angeles)|Ulysses S. Grant High School]]. The NHHS Athletics Department offers:\n[[Archery]],\n[[Baseball]],\n[[Basketball]] (boys' and girls'),\n[[Cheerleading]],\n[[Cross country running|Cross Country]],\n[[American football|Football]],\n[[Golf]],\n[[Soccer]] (boys' and girls'),\n[[Softball]] (girls'),\n[[Students Run LA]],\n[[Tennis]],\n[[Track & Field]],\n[[Ultimate Frisbee]],\n[[Volleyball]] (boys' and girls'), and\n[[Weight Training]].\n\n===Performing Arts===\n[[File:NHHS Instrumental Music Room.jpg|thumb|''The instrumental music room.'']]\n[[File:NHHS Auditorium.jpg|thumb|''The auditorium.'']]\nNHHS offers a wide variety of performing arts courses.\n\n*[[Marching Band]] - During the Fall semester, the marching band is typically a Division 2A, 70-member ensemble called the ''Royal Regiment''. The band performs as a [[pep band]] at football games and competes in field tournaments.\n*[[Concert Band]] - During the Spring semester, the marching band becomes a concert band that performs at festivals, the annual Spring Concert, and various school events.\n*[[String Orchestra]] - During the Fall semester, the string orchestra prepares and performs for the annual Winter Concert.\n*[[Symphony Orchestra|Advanced Symphony Orchestra]] - During the Spring semester, the string orchestra becomes a symphony orchestra, inviting the Concert Band's top wind and percussion musicians to round out the ensemble. The orchestra performs at festivals and the annual Spring Concert.\n*[[Percussion Ensemble]] - During the Fall semester, the percussion ensemble prepares and performs for the annual Winter Concert.\n*[[Indoor percussion ensemble|Indoor Drumline]] - During the Spring semester, the indoor drumline performs in drumline tournaments, the annual Spring Percussion Concert, and various school events. \n*[[Jazz Band|Advanced Jazz Band]] - Meeting before school during both semesters, the jazz band is an approximately 20-member ensemble that performs in festivals, the annual Winter Concert, the annual Spring Concert, and various events.\n*[[Guitar|Beginning Guitar]] - During both semesters, beginning guitars is an introductory-level class for students with interest in guitar.\n*[[Choir|Vocal Ensemble]] - During both semesters, the vocal ensemble is the most advanced group that prepares and performs for festivals, the annual Winter Concert, and the annual Spring Concert.\n*[[Choir|Chorus]] - During both semesters, the chorus prepares and performs for the annual Winter Concert and the annual Spring Concert.\n*[[Choir|Beginning Choir]] - During both semesters, the beginning choir is an introductory-level class for students with no musical background.\n*[[Color guard (flag spinning)|Color Guard]] - During the Fall semester, the color guard teams up with the marching band to perform at football games and compete in field tournaments.\n*[[Dance Team]] - During the Spring semester, the colorguard becomes a dance team that performs in competitions and the annual Spring Dance Show.\n\n==Demographics==\nFor the 2018-19 school year, NHHS had a total enrollment of 2,522 students, broken down into 29.9% freshmen, 25.8% sophomores, 21.6% juniors, and 22.7% seniors. 9.6% of NHHS students were English Learners.<ref>https://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/dqcensus/EnrEthGrd.aspx?cds=19647331936350&agglevel=school&year=2018-19</ref>\n\nDuring the 2014-15 school year, the [[student-teacher ratio]] was 24 to 1, and NHHS had 11 administrators, 114 teachers, and 10 pupil services workers. Of the 114 teachers, 1 has a [[Doctorate]], 61 have [[Master's degrees]], 48 have [[Bachelor's degrees]], and 4 were unreported.<ref>[http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/Staff/StaffEduLvl.aspx?cSelect=North^Hollywood^Seni--Los^Angeles^Uni--1964733-1936350&cYear=2014-15&cChoice=SchEduc&cType=T&cGender=B&cLevel=School&cTopic=Paif&myTimeFrame=S] {{dead link|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n{|border = \"1\" style = \"text-align: left; border-collapse: collapse; width:25%\"\n! Ethnicity !! Students (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/dqcensus/EnrEthLevels.aspx?cds=19647331936350&agglevel=School&year=2017-18|title=Enrollment by Ethnicity - North Hollywood Senior High School (CA Dept of Education)|website=Dq.cde.ca.gov}}</ref>!! Teachers (2018)<ref>https://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/Staff/StaffByEth.aspx?cSelect=North^Hollywood^Seni--Los^Angeles^Uni--1964733-1936350&cYear=2017-18&cChoice=SchTeach&cType=T&cGender=B&cLevel=School&cTopic=Paif&myTimeFrame=S</ref> \n|-\n| Hispanic or Latino || 69.7% || 27.2%\n|-\n| White || 15.6% || 57.9%\n|-\n| Asian || 7.8% || 3.5%\n|-\n| Black or African American || 3.6% || 5.2%\n|-\n| Filipino || 1.9% || 2.6%\n|-\n| American Indian or Alaska Native || 0.3% || 0.8%\n|- \n| Pacific Islander || 0.2% || 0.8%\n|-\n| Other/Not Reported || 1.0% || 1.7%\n|}\n\n==Achievements==\n*At the California [[Academic Decathlon]], NHHS won 8th place in 2001, 4th place in 2002, 7th place in 2005, 9th place in 2006, 4th place in 2007, 5th place in 2008, 3rd place in 2009, 45th place in 2013, 46th place in 2014, 31st place in 2015, 51st place in 2016, 8th place in Division 3 in 2017, and 12th place in Division 2 in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academicdecathlon.org/scores.htm|title=California Academic Decathlon Website|website=Academicdecathlon.org}}</ref>\n*At the Regional [[Science Bowl]], NHHS has won 1st place every year since 1998, missing only 2005 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/North-Hollywood-High-School-LADWP-Science-Bowl--369559891.html|title=North Hollywood High School Wins Science Bowl|website=Nbclosangeles.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-north-hollywood-science-20170226-story.html|title=North Hollywood High School wins LADWP Science Bowl|first=Brittny|last=Mejia|date=26 February 2017|website=Latimes.com}}</ref> At the National [[Science Bowl]], NHHS won 1st place in 2001,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2001/may/08/local/me-60825 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Massie | last=Ritsch | title=North Hollywood High Wins U.S. Science Bowl | date=2001-05-08}}</ref> 2nd place in 2006, 6th place in 2008, 10th place in 2009, 3rd place in 2010, 2nd place in 2012, 7th place in 2013, 5th place in 2016, 9th place in 2017, and 2nd place in 2018.\n*At the [[National Ocean Sciences Bowl]]'s Los Angeles Surf Bowl, NHHS won 3rd place in 2012.\n*At the [[CSU Long Beach]] Math Day at the Beach, NHHS won 1st place in 2006, 2nd place in 2012, 5th place in 2013, and 4th place in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/beach-609065-high-competition.html|title=Troy, University high schools top math competition|date=10 April 2014|website=Ocregister.com}}</ref>\n*At the Regional [[Mandelbrot Competition]], NHHS ranked 42nd place in 2011 and 39th place in 2012. At the National [[Mandelbrot Competition]], NHHS ranked 50th place in 2011 and 73rd place in 2012.\n*At the Regional [[FIRST Robotics Competition]], NHHS's NohoRobo Team was a quarterfinalist and received the Rookie Inspiration Award in 2010, and was a 6th seed (of 66) semifinalist in 2015.\n*At the International [[Botball]] Competition, NHHS received the Outstanding Programming award and the Judges' Choice award in 2011. At the Greater Los Angeles Regional Botball Tournament, NHHS won 2nd place overall in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.botball.org/gla/2017/results|title=2017 Greater Los Angeles Regional Botball\u00ae Tournament Results - Botball\u00ae Educational Robotics Program|website=Botball.org}}</ref>\n*At the Duke [[Moot Court]] National Tournament, NHHS has won 1st place in 2009, 1st and 2nd place in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sites.duke.edu/dukemootcourt/high-school-tournament/previous-high-school-tournaments/|title=Previous Tournaments and Cases - Duke Moot Court|website=Sites.duke.edu}}</ref> was a semifinalist in 2012 and won 2nd place in 2016.\n*At the [http://www.crf-usa.org/ Constitutional Rights Foundation]'s Mock Trial State Competition, NHHS won 1st place in 1982 and 2nd place in 1983.\n*At the [[National Speech and Debate Association]]'s district qualifier, NHHS's [[speech and debate]] team won sweepstakes in [[Congressional Debate]] in 2014. In three of [[California High School Speech Association]]'s Tri-County Forensics League competitions, NHHS's team took sweepstakes in 2014. At the CHSSA's state championships, NHHS students won 10th and 11th in Congressional Debate.\n*At the National [[National Academic Quiz Tournaments|NAQT]] Tournament, NHHS won 43rd in 2009, 21st in 2012, and 33rd in 2013.\n*At the [[CyberPatriot]] National Finals, NHHS won 4th and 6th place in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhhs.net/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=288879&id=0 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224034507/http://www.nhhs.net/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=288879&id=0 |archivedate=2014-02-24 }} </ref> 1st place in 2014,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2014/mar/31/local/la-me-ln-north-hollywood-high-wins-cyber-security-20140331 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Alicia | last=Banks | title=North Hollywood High wins national cyber-security competition | date=2014-03-31}}</ref> and 2nd and 5th place in 2015. At the California Cyber Innovation Challenge, NHHS won 1st place in 2016 and 2017.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160921210235/http://www.techwire.net/innovation/high-school-teams-compete-in-go-biz-cyber-innovation-challenge.html] </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://calpolynews.calpoly.edu/news_releases/2017/07/cyber|title=North Hollywood High School Wins California Cyber Innovation Challenge Competition at Cal Poly - Cal Poly News - Cal Poly, San Luis Obispo|website=Calpolynews.calpoly.edu}}</ref> In 2017, three teams were sent to the national finals and one team won 1st place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-edu-north-hollywood-computers-champs-20170408-story.html|title=North Hollywood High team wins national cybersecurity competition|first=Howard|last=Blume|date=8 April 2017|website=Latimes.com}}</ref>. In 2018, three teams were sent to the national finals and won 1st, 2nd, and 9th place. In 2019, NHHS won 2nd place in the Open Class Division.\n*The NHHS [[National FFA Organization|FFA]] chapter was ranked a \"Superior Chapter\" by the California FFA Association in 1951, 1953, 1954, 1957, 1958, 1959, 1960, 1963, 1967, 1980, 1989, and 1990. At the Los Angeles [[National FFA Organization|FFA]] Horticulture Contest, NHHS teams won 1st place in both Advanced Horticulture and Floral Horticulture in 2015.\n*At the Southern California [[DECA (organization)|DECA]] Conference, NHHS won 1st and 2nd place in marketing, and 1st place in business law and ethics in 2016.\n*The NHHS Baseball Team won the title of city champions in 1957 and 2012, and was a city championships runner-up in 1949, 1980, and 2011.\n*The NHHS Boys' Basketball Team won the title of city champions in 1990, and was a city championships runner-up in 1959, 1960, 1978, 1991, 2000, and 2003.\n*The NHHS Girls' Basketball Team won the title of city champions in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/highschool/varsity-times/la-sp-vi-girls-basketball-north-hollywood-wins-its-first-city-section-title-in-division-ii-20160304-story.html|title=Girls' basketball: North Hollywood wins its first City Section title in Division II|first=Eric|last=Sondheimer|date=4 March 2016|website=Latimes.com}}</ref> and was a runner-up in 1987, 1988, and 1993.\n*The NHHS Cheerleading Team won 1st place at DREAM TEAM Championships in 2011, 2nd place at YPI's Dance-Drill-Cheer Competition in 2014 and 4th place at City CIF Cheer Championships in 2018.\n*The NHHS Varsity Football Team was undefeated and league champions in 2004 and 2007.\n*The NHHS Junior-Varsity Football Team finished 10-1 and were League Champions in the 2017 Season, with two non-consecutive 5 game winning streaks.\n*The NHHS Girls' Golf Team won the title of city champions in 2010, and won individual champions in 2008 and 2009.\n*The NHHS Boys' Tennis Team was undefeated and league champions in 2017.\n*The NHHS Girls' Tennis Team won the title of Division II city champions in 2015.\n*The NHHS Boys' Volleyball Team won the title of city champions in 2000.\n*The NHHS Girls' Soccer Team won the title of city champions of Div II in 2020. \n*At the [[LAUSD]] Band and Dance Team Championships, the NHHS Royal Regiment won 1st place in 1985, 1986, 1989, 1991, 1993, 1997, 1998, 2001, 2002, 2004, and 2018.\n*At the [[Southern California Band and Orchestra Association]] marching band circuit, the NHHS Royal Regiment was a finalist in 2004, 2005, and 2006.\n*At the [http://www.drumsacrosscalifornia.com/ Drums Across California]'s [[Indoor percussion ensemble|Indoor Drumline]] Championships, the NHHS Indoor Drumline won 5th place in 2012, 4th place in 2013, 3rd place in 2014, 2nd place in 2015, 1st place in 2016, 2nd place in 2017, 1st place in 2018, and 1st place in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.drumsacrosscalifornia.com/DAC_Hall_of_Fame_Winners.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404214034/http://drumsacrosscalifornia.com/DAC_Hall_of_Fame_Winners.html |archivedate=2016-04-04 }} </ref>\n*At the [[LAUSD]] Drumline Championships, the NHHS [[Indoor percussion ensemble|Indoor Drumline]] won 2nd place in 2012, 2nd place in 2013, and 4th place in 2014.\n*In 2011, Mr. Randall Delling was named California Secondary Principal of the Year by the Association of California School Administrators.<ref>https://www.huffingtonpost.com/laura-sturza/north-hollywood-high-washington-post_b_952735.html</ref> In 2014, Mr. Jay Gehringer was named LAUSD Teacher of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laschoolreport.com/lausd-honors-22-educators-teacher-year/|title=LAUSD honors 22 educators as 'Teachers of the Year' - LA School Report|website=Laschoolreport.com}}</ref> In 2015, Mr. Altair Maine was named LAUSD Teacher of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.lausd.net/apps/news/article/470518|title=LAUSD Salutes 22 Educators as 'Teachers of the Year'|website=Home.lausd.net}}</ref> In 2016, Ms. Carrie Schwartz was named Secondary Co-Administrator of the Year by the Association of California School Administrators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acsa.org/About-Us/awards-program|title=ACSA Awards Program|website=Acsa.org}}</ref> In 2018, alum Ms. Dorothy Williams-Kohlmeyer was named LAUSD Rookie of the Year.<ref>http://csunshinetoday.csun.edu/arts-and-culture/alumna-dance-teacher-wins-rookie-teacher-of-the-year-award</ref>\n*As of 2018, NHHS has a graduation rate of 92.3%.<ref>https://www.caschooldashboard.org/reports/19647331936350/2018#graduation-rate-card</ref>\n\n==Filming location==\nNHHS has been the filming location for movies, television shows, and other productions, including the following:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/search/title|title=IMDb: Most Popular Titles With Location Matching \"North Hollywood High School - 5231 Colfax Avenue, North Hollywood, Los Angeles, California, USA\"|website=IMDb.com}}</ref>\n\n*[[The Human Comedy (film)|The Human Comedy]] (1943)\n*[[The Rockford Files]] (1974-1980)\n*[[The White Shadow (TV series)|The White Shadow]] (1978-1981)\n*[[Demolition High]] (1996)\n*[[Joan of Arcadia]] (2003-2005)\n*The Lockhavens (2009)\n*The Tudor Tutor (2010)\n*[[Shameless (American TV series)|Shameless]] Season 4, Episode 9 \"The Legend of Bonnie and Carl\" (2014)\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{refimprove section|date=November 2015}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[DJ Khalil|Khalil Abdul-Rahman]], music producer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/01/sports/la-sp-0701-crowe-20100701|title=NBA free agency might end up as boring rerun|first=Jerry|last=Crowe|date=1 July 2010|website=Articles.latimes.com}}</ref>\n*[[Larry Agran]], politician, U.S. Presidential candidate\n*[[Harry Anderson]], actor<ref>https://news.avclub.com/r-i-p-harry-anderson-actor-magician-and-star-of-nig-1825307688</ref>\n*[[Tony Angell]], artist, author\n*[[Brian Baima]], American football player\n*[[Noah Beery, Jr.]], actor\n*[[Stuart Benjamin]], film producer\n*[[Richard Beymer]], actor\n*[[Mayim Bialik]], actress\n*[[DJ Bonebrake|Donald \"D.J.\" Bonebrake]], musician\n*[[Perry Botkin Jr.]], musician, composer, producer\n*[[Ron Brand]], former Major League baseball player\n*[[Michael Broggie]], author, historian\n*[[Barbara S. Brogliatti|Barbara Brogliatti]], public relations, marketing executive\n*[[Bill Cable]], actor, model\n*[[Christy Canyon]], actress\n*[[Cindy Carol]], actress\n*[[Adam Carolla]], comedian\n*[[Nick Cassavetes]], director, actor\n*[[Sydney Chaplin]], actor<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/mar/10/sydney-chaplin-obituary</ref>\n*[[Bert Convy]], actor, singer, game show host\n*[[Andrei Cherny]], author, politician\n*[[Jordan Cronenweth]], cinematographer\n*[[Gary Crosby (actor)|Gary Crosby]], actor, singer\n*[[Sandy Descher]], child actress<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1913&dat=19630413&id=i7QgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vmkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5795,4481824&hl=en</ref>\n*[[Dean Devlin]], producer, writer, actor\n*[[Maureen Dragone]], journalist, author and founder of the [[Young Artist Award]]s\n*[[Denis Dutton]], media activist, web entrepreneur\n*[[Edan Everly]], musician\n*[[Shelley Fabares]], actress\n*[[Stanley Fafara]], actor\n*[[Tiger Fafara]], actor\n*[[Brent Fischer]], composer/arranger\n*[[George Frenn]], Olympian\n*[[Rob Friedman]], co-chairman of [[Lionsgate Motion Picture Group]]\n*[[Ernestine Fu]], venture capital investor, author<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/susanadams/2011/05/13/names-you-need-to-know-ernestine-fu/#2957ca523002|title=Names You Need to Know: Ernestine Fu|first=Susan|last=Adams|website=Forbes.com}}</ref>\n*[[Carrington Garland]], actress\n*[[Teri Garr]], actress<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patch.com/california/studiocity/north-hollywood-high-school-reunion-brings-back-the-memories|title=North Hollywood High School Reunion Brings Back the Memories|date=27 June 2011|website=Patch.com}}</ref>\n*[[Cuba Gooding Jr.]], actor\n*[[Omar Gooding]], actor\n*[[Danso Gordon]], actor\n*[[Farley Granger]], actor\n*[[Brian Austin Green|Brian Green]], actor\n*[[Bruce Guerin]], child actor, pianist<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/bruce-guerin-child-actor-who-became-a-star-thanks-to-his-work-with-josef-von-sternberg-8036651.html</ref>\n*[[Ruben and the Jets|Ruben Guevara]], musician\n*[[Don Hahn]], film producer\n*[[Khrystyne Haje]], actress\n*[[Alyson Hannigan]], actress\n*[[David W. Harper|David Harper]], actor\n*[[Jamake Highwater]], writer, journalist\n*[[William Hohri]], activist\n*[[Desiree Horton]], TV personality, helicopter pilot\n*[[Julia Hu]], technology entrepreneur\n*[[Michael Hutchence]], musician, lead singer of Australian band [[INXS]]\n*[[Sasha Jenson]], actor\n*[[Andy Johnson (basketball)|Andy Johnson]], former NBA player\n*[[Dana Jones]], basketball player\n*[[Janet Julian]], actress\n*[[Andrew Koenig|Josh \"Andrew\" Koenig]], actor\n*[[J-five|Jonathan Kovacs]], singer\n*[[Alan Ladd]], actor\n*[[Louis Landon]], pianist{{Citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n*[[Arthur Lee (basketball)|Arthur Lee]], basketball player\n*[[Jonah Lehrer]], author\n*[[Pam Ling]], physician, castmate on [[The Real World: San Francisco]]\n*[[Barry Livingston]], actor\n*[[Stanley Livingston]], actor\n*[[Marlon Lucky]], American football player\n*[[Heather MacRae]], vocalist, actress\n*[[Meredith MacRae]], actress\n*[[Ralph Mauriello]]. former Major League baseball player\n*[[Mike McDonald (American football)|Mike McDonald]], former NFL player\n*[[Jake McLaughlin]], actor\n*[[Nick McLean]], cinematographer\n*[[Jimmy McNichol]], actor\n*[[Nick Menza]], drummer/percussionist\n*[[Martin Milner]], actor\n*[[Aaron Mitchell (American football)|Aaron Mitchell]], former NFL player\n*[[Rolando Molina]], actor\n*[[Johanna Moore]], computer scientist\n*[[Erin Moran]], actress\n*[[Michael Nassir]], astronomer\n*[[Ken Osmond]], actor\n*[[Gerald P. Pulley|Gerald Pulley]], U.S. Navy photographer\n*[[Eduard Punset]], Spanish politician, lawyer, economist, science popularizer<ref>https://www.eitb.eus/es/noticias/sociedad/detalle/6423825/eduard-punset-biografia-divulgador-fallecido-22-mayo-2019/</ref>\n*[[Alan Robbins]], politician\n*[[Bob Ronka]], Los Angeles City Council member, 1977\u201381.\n*[[Barbara Ruick]], actress, singer\n*[[Jennifer Runyon]], actress\n*[[Maia Sharp]], singer, songwriter\n*[[Amy Sherman-Palladino]], producer, director, writer\n*[[Shields and Yarnell|Robert Shields]], mime, actor\n*[[Daniel Wayne Smith|Daniel Smith]], son of [[Anna Nicole Smith]]<ref>https://nymag.com/news/features/anna-nicole-smith-2011-6/index7.html</ref>\n*[[Shawnee Smith]], actress, musician\n*[[Susan Sontag]], author, theorist, activist\n*[[Joshua Stangby]], NFL/CFL wide receiver<ref>https://www.latimes.com/tn-gnp-former-glendale-community-college-football-player-joshua-stangby-signs-with-atlanta-falcons-20150506-story.html</ref>\n*[[Mary Kay Stearns]], actress\n*[[Robert C. Stebbins|Robert Stebbins]], biologist, illustrator\n*[[Guy Sularz]], former Major League baseball player\n*[[Beth Sullivan]], screenwriter, executive producer\n*[[Robert Swink]], film editor\n*[[Anthony Sydes]], actor, Purple Heart recipient\n*[[Margaret Talbot]], essayist\n*[[Russ Tamblyn]], actor, dancer\n*[[Anthony 'Scooter' Teague]], actor, dancer\n*[[Michael Tilson Thomas]], musician, composer, director of the [[San Francisco Symphony]]\n*[[Ernest E. Tissot Jr.|Eugene Tissot, Jr.]], U.S. Navy Rear Admiral\n*[[Ronne Troup]], actress<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beta.worldcat.org/archivegrid/collection/data/503582390|title=ArchiveGrid : Ronne Troup, North Hollywood High School songleader [graphic] / photo by Alan Hyde.|work=worldcat.org}}</ref>\n*[[Ron Unz]], entrepreneur, political activist\n*[[Benny Urquidez]], kickboxer<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/1985-08-17/sports/sp-2240_1_benny-urquidez | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Steve | last=Henson | title=The Jet : Born to Brawl, Benny Urquidez Lived Through a Death Match to Become One of the Greatest Unknown Fighters in America | date=August 17, 1985}}</ref>\n*[[Morgan Webb]], TV personality\n*[[Julius Wechter]], bandleader of [[Baja Marimba Band]]\n*[[Eugene M. Wescott|Eugene Wescott]], geophysicist\n*[[Jim Wheeler]], politician\n*[[De'voreaux White]], actor\n*[[John Williams]], composer, conductor, pianist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nceagletimes.com/other-news/2014/11/13/john-williams-a-music-genius/|title=John Williams\u2013A Music Genius!|first=Sarah|last=Lara|website=Nceagletimes.com}}</ref>\n*[[Melanie Wilson (actress)|Melanie Wilson]], actress\n*[[Lauren Woodland]], actress, attorney\n*[[Scott Yancey]], TV personality\n*[[Charles Yukl]], ragtime pianist, murderer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/piano-man-article-1.275907|title=The Piano Man|website=Nydailynews.com}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Greater Los Angeles|Schools}}\n{{Commons category|North Hollywood High School}}\n*[http://www.nhhs.net/ North Hollywood High School website]\n*Articles about [https://articles.latimes.com/keyword/north-hollywood-high-school \"North Hollywood High School\"] - ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n\n{{North Hollywood, Los Angeles}}\n{{San Fernando Valley Schools}}\n{{LAUSD}}\n\n[[Category:Magnet schools in California]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Unified School District schools]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1927]]\n[[Category:High schools in the San Fernando Valley]]\n[[Category:High schools in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in California]]\n[[Category:North Hollywood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n|name              = North Hollywood High School\n|image             = NHHS Kennedy Hall.jpg\n|imagesize         = \n|streetaddress     = 5231 Colfax Avenue\n|city              = [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|North Hollywood]]\n|state             = [[California]]\n|zipcode           = 91601\n|country           = [[United States]]\n|coordinates       = {{coord|34|09|57|N|118|23|20|W|type:edu_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|pushpin_map = United States San Fernando Valley#United States Los Angeles Metropolitan Area#USA California#United States\n|schooltype        = [[high school]]\n|type              = [[Public high school|Public]]\n|established       = 1927\n|status            = Open\n|district          = [[Los Angeles Unified School District]]\n|superintendent    = [[Austin Beutner]]\n|principal         = Ricardo Rosales\n|faculty           = 118\n|grades            = [[Ninth grade|9]]-[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n|age range         = 14-18\n|enrollment        = 2,501 (2018)<ref>https://www.ed-data.org/school/Los-Angeles/Los-Angeles-Unified/North-Hollywood-Senior-High</ref>\n|grade9            = 749\n|grade10           = 649\n|grade11           = 537\n|grade12           = 566\n|ratio             = 21:1\n|language          = [[English language|English]]\n|hours_in_day      = 7 hours 16 minutes (Monday, Wednesday-Friday)<br />6 hours 10 minutes (Tuesday)\n|campus            = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|colors            = {{Color box|blue|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}{{Color box|gray|border=darkgray}} Blue, White, Gray\n|song              = Huskies Are We\n|conference        = East Valley League<br>CIF Los Angeles City Section\n|mascot            = Huskies\n|nickname          = Huskies, Big Blue\n|rival             = [[Polytechnic High School (Los Angeles)|Polytechnic High School]]<br />[[Grant High School (Los Angeles)|Ulysses S. Grant High School]]\n|SAT               = 485 Reading<br />481 Math<br />482 Writing<br />1448 Average (2016)\n|ACT               = 23 Reading<br />22 Math<br />22 English<br />21 Science<br />22 Average (2016)\n|newspaper         = The Arcade\n|feeders           = [[Walter Reed Middle School]]<br>Sun Valley Middle School<br>Roy Romer Middle School<br>Gaspar de Portola Middle School\n|homepage          = [http://nhhs.net/ NHHS]<br>[http://highlygiftedmagnet.org/ NHHS HGM]<br>[http://zoomagnet.org/ NHHS Zoo Magnet]<br>[http://royalregiment.org/ NHHS Music]\n| module        = {{Infobox mapframe\n| stroke-color = #C60C30\n| stroke-width  = 3\n| marker        = school\n| marker-color = #1F2F57\n| zoom          = 13}}\n}}\n\n'''North Hollywood High School''' is a [[public high school]] in [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles, California|North Hollywood]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]. NHHS is located in the [[San Fernando Valley]] and enrolls approximately 2,500 students each year. Several neighborhoods, including most of [[North Hollywood, California|North Hollywood]], [[Valley Village, Los Angeles, California|Valley Village]], [[Studio City, Los Angeles, California|Studio City]] and [[Sun Valley, Los Angeles, California|Sun Valley]], send students to this school. As of 2019, NHHS is accredited by the [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]. As of 2019, the [[school principal]] is Mr. Ricardo Rosales.\n\n==Facilities==\nThe campus facilities include three main buildings (Kennedy Hall, Frasher Hall, and Randolph Hall), an agricultural area with livestock, a garden, an auditorium, a cafeteria, two gymnasiums, multiple computer labs with internet access, an auto mechanic shop, a wood shop, an instrumental music room, a football field, two softball fields, a baseball diamond, two tennis court areas, a teachers' parking lot, an art room, a college center, a parent center, a student store, and a library.\n\n==History==\n[[File:NHHS Student Quad.jpg|thumb|''The student quad.'']]\nBuilt in 1927, '''Lankershim High School''' was named for the town of Lankershim (first called Toluca, now North Hollywood) and its founding family. It opened with only a main building, auditorium, gymnasium, and a shop & mechanics building, with 800 students, graduating its first class in 1928. The Board of Education was asked to employ teachers who were already residents of North Hollywood, creating jobs and education opportunities right in the area. Lankershim High School was renamed '''North Hollywood High School''' in 1929. In 1937, a girls' gymnasium and a second major classroom building, now named Frasher Hall after former principal Roscoe Frasher, were built. In 1950, the third major classroom building, now named Randolph Hall, was built. In the 1950s, many smaller construction projects took place, including the agricultural classrooms, the boys' gymnasium, the home-side bleachers, and the instrumental music room. In 1965, the main hall was named the [[John F. Kennedy]] Memorial Hall after the slain President. In 1966, the cafeteria, student store, and two shop buildings were built. In 1973, the Amelia Earhart Continuation High School was built on the campus' Northeast corner. In the late 1990s, thirteen modular buildings were installed to support an increase in the number of students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/16/news/mn-20297/3|title=L.A. Unified May Need High Schools to Go Year-Round|first1=DOUG|last1=SMITH|first2=KRISTINA|last2=SAUERWEIN|date=16 April 2000|website=Articles.latimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===1990s and beyond===\nIn 1996, the LAUSD board voted to move NHHS to a [[year-round school|year-round schedule]], but after more classroom space was found, the board reversed course. Several NHHS parents and community members did not want a year-round schedule since they feared it would negatively impact the [[Highly Gifted Magnet]].<ref name=Sauerweinmaythreaten>Sauerwein, Kristina. \"[https://articles.latimes.com/1999/sep/30/local/me-16638 Enrollment May Threaten Program for Highly Gifted].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. September 30, 1999. Retrieved on January 9, 2016.</ref> According to the 1996 scheduling magnet students were supposed to get July\u2013May, which would have impacted their ability to attend summer programs operated by [[Ivy League]] universities. The zoo magnet students were to get the September\u2013June schedule.<ref>Folmar, Kate. \"[https://articles.latimes.com/1996-03-02/local/me-42077_1_north-hollywood North Hollywood : High School to Review Its Magnet Scheduling].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. March 2, 1996. Retrieved on January 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2000, [[Ramon C. Cortines]], the LAUSD superintendent, stated that the overcrowding at NHHS was more severe than originally anticipated,<ref>Sauerwein, Kristina. \"[https://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/06/local/me-16675 Cortines Deals Blow to High School Schedule Fight].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. April 6, 2000. Retrieved on January 9, 2016.</ref> and he announced that NHHS was going year-round. This was despite parents and students protesting against the move for several months.<ref>Sauerwein, Kristina. \"[https://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/08/local/me-17333 New N. Hollywood High Schedule Incites Anger].\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. April 8, 2000. Retrieved on January 9, 2016.</ref> From 2000 to 2007, NHHS was a year-round school with three tracks.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/08/local/me-17330 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Kristina | last=Sauerwein | title=North Hollywood High to Begin Year-Round Calendar | date=2000-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, [[East Valley High School (Los Angeles)|East Valley High School]] opened, relieving overcrowding at NHHS.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/04/local/me-schools4 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Howard | last=Blume | title=School Spirit Is Given a Boost in the Valley | date=2006-10-04}}</ref> In 2007, the traditional calendar was re-adopted and the students were divided into many [[Small Learning Communities]] (SLCs).  All but three of these SLCs were closed in June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laschools.org/planlausd/surveys/V-2%20%207%20Schools/VERSION%202-%20North%20Hollywood%20HS.pdf|title=North Hollywood High School: Campus Pre-Planning Survey|website=Laschools.org|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, it was announced that NHHS was selected to undergo major renovations, including upgrading buildings and removing portable buildings, to be completed in five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patch.com/california/northhollywood/north-hollywood-high-school-be-fast-tracked-major-rennovations|title=North Hollywood High School to Be Fast-Tracked for Major Rennovations(sic)|date=28 January 2015|website=Patch.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 there was a proposal to co-locate a charter school, Valley International Preparatory High School (VIPHS), on the NHHS campus, but there was student opposition; students created an online petition to oppose the co-location.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2018/03/03/north-hollywood-high-may-have-to-share-its-campus-with-a-charter-school-and-some-students-arent-happy-about-it/|title=North Hollywood High may have to share its campus with a charter school, and these students aren't happy about it|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|date=2018-03-03|accessdate=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nNHHS contains three [[magnet school|magnet programs]]; the [[Highly Gifted Magnet]] (HGM), the Zoo Magnet, and the STEM Magnet. There are also three [[Small Learning Communities]] (SLCs); the Humanitas School for Advanced Studies, the Home Engineering Academy, and the Freshmen Academy.\n\n===Highly Gifted Magnet===\nThe [[Highly Gifted Magnet]] was established in 1989, and is a component of the voluntary integration program of the LAUSD, designed to provide an academically challenging college preparatory program. The program is designed to prepare its students to thrive in the most demanding of university environments. The students in the HGM are from all over Los Angeles, and have a variety of extracurricular interests, as well as diversity in their academic directions.\n\nChildren are eligible if they test in the 99.5th percentile or above on an intelligence test conducted by an LAUSD psychologist. Priority is given to children with 99.9%, officially \u201cHighly Gifted\u201d by LAUSD definition. If there are openings remaining in the program, \u201cGifted\u201d students with 99.5%-99.8% may be admitted with priority based on magnet points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highlygiftedmagnet.org/how-to-apply/|title=Eligibility & Admissions|website=The Highly Gifted Magnet}}</ref> The program had 265 students,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highlygiftedmagnet.org/about/|title=About the HGM|website=The Highly Gifted Magnet}}</ref> 4 administrators, and 7 faculty members in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highlygiftedmagnet.org/faculty/|title=Contact Faculty & Admin|website=The Highly Gifted Magnet}}</ref>\n\n===Zoo Magnet===\n[[File:NHHS Cafeteria.jpg|thumb|''The student cafeteria.'']]\nThe Zoo Magnet was established in 1981, and is a specialized school that buses students to a small campus next to the [[Los Angeles Zoo]] in [[Griffith Park]]. At this site, approximately 300 students take standard classes such as history, math, and English, in addition to [[Advanced Placement]] classes related to biological and [[zoology|zoological sciences]]. Many of these classes include fieldwork in the [[Los Angeles Zoo|Los Angeles Zoo and Botanical Gardens]], [[Los Angeles River]] ecosystem, [[Autry National Center]] and the natural world of [[Griffith Park]] for tours and observation. Classes are on a block schedule, meeting three days a week for two hours per class.\n\n===STEM Magnet===\nThe STEM Magnet was established in 2018, and is an alternative course of study that prepares students for college and career opportunities in Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math.\n\n===Small Learning Communities===\nThe [[Small Learning Communities]] (SLCs) are intended to increase student achievement by personalizing the educational experience of students in large schools. Of the eight SLCs originally created, three remain as of 2019; the Humanitas School for Advanced Studies (HSAS), the Home Engineering Academy (HEA), and the Freshmen Academy (FA). The HSAS is designed for identified gifted, high achieving, high-ability students who show an interest in taking Honors and [[Advanced Placement]] courses. The HEA specializes in the construction and building trades.\n\n===Rankings===\nIn 2020, [[Niche (company)|Niche]] designated NHHS as #279 in the country, and was awarded an overall grade of \"A\", with an A- in Academics, an A- in Diversity, an A in Teachers, an A in College Prep, a B- in Clubs and Activities, a B in Health and Safety, a B in Administration, a C+ in Sports, a C in Food, and a C in Resources and Facilities.<ref>https://www.niche.com/k12/north-hollywood-senior-high-school-north-hollywood-ca/rankings/</ref>\n\nIn 2020, ''[[Newsweek]]'' ranked NHHS as #2183 in the country for STEM programs, with a score of 63.6/100.<ref>https://www.newsweek.com/americas-best-stem-high-schools-2020/best-stem-schools-2001-2500</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranked NHHS as 1,558th in the country, 233rdd of all high schools in California, 98th in Los Angeles, and gave it a College Readiness Index of 39/100. It also ranked the Highly Gifted Magnet as 192nd in the country.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/california/districts/los-angeles-unified-school-district/north-hollywood-senior-high-2573</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the [[California Standardized Testing and Reporting Program|California Assessment of Student Performance and Progress]] evaluated 11th grade students in English and Mathematics. In the area of English, 11th grade students were classified as 15% standard not met, 17% standard nearly met, 32% standard met, and 36% stanard exceeded. In the area of Math, 11th grade students were classified as 37% standard not met, 26% standard nearly met, 17% standard met, and 20% standard exceeded.<ref>https://caaspp.cde.ca.gov/sb2018/ViewReport?ps=true&lstTestYear=2018&lstTestType=B&lstGroup=1&lstCounty=19&lstDistrict=64733-000&lstSchool=1936350</ref>\n\nIn 2018, schooldigger.com ranked NHHS as 416th of all high schools in California, 25th of all high schools in LAUSD, and 2nd of all public/non-magnet high schools in LAUSD.<ref>https://www.schooldigger.com/go/CA/schools/2271003230/school.aspx</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the ''[[Washington Post]]'' ranked NHHS as 624th in the country, 77th of all high schools in California, 58th of all public high schools in California, 21st of all high schools in Los Angeles County, 11th of all high schools in LAUSD, and 1st of all high schools in District 2.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/local/high-school-challenge-2017/|title=U.S. high school rankings by state \u2014 Most challenging schools|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2017-18 school year, the average [[ACT Test]] scores were a 25 in Reading, a 25 in English, a 24 in Math, and a 24 in Science, each out of 36 points.<ref>https://data1.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/satactap/CollegeTest?cdscode=19647331936350&CollegeTest=act&year=2017-18</ref>\n\nIn 2016, LAUSD's new School Quality Improvement Index<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home.lausd.net/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=227154&type=d&pREC_ID=657699 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205212658/http://home.lausd.net/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=227154&type=d&pREC_ID=657699 |archivedate=2016-02-05 }} </ref> scored NHHS's 2014-15 year as 80/100, broken down into 10.51/15 in Academic Performance English Language Arts (64% met or exceeded standards), 12.01/15 in Academic Performance Math (37% met or exceeded standards), 11.25/20 in Four Year Cohort Graduation Rate (85% graduated class of 2014), 3.7/5 in Five Year Cohort Graduation Rate (90% graduated class of 2013), 3.51/5 in Six Year Cohort Graduation Rate (89% graduated class of 2012), 12.68/13.33 in Chronic Absenteeism (6% chronically absent), 13.35/13.33 in Suspension Rates (0% suspended/expelled), and 13.33/13.33 in English Learner Re-Designation (21% re-designated).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatschools.org/catalog/CORE_districts/LAUSD-NE/Abridged/North_Hollywood_Senior_High-19647331936350-hs.pdf|title=NORTH HOLLYWOOD SENIOR HIGH|date=28 March 2016|website=Greatschools.org|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave NHHS a grade of \"A\" in arts education, ranking it 6th of all secondary schools, and 9th of all schools within LAUSD. Out of over 700 schools, only 35 received an \"A\" grade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://schools.latimes.com/grading-the-arts/north-hollywood-senior-high-secondary/|title=North Hollywood Senior High|work=schools.latimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, ''[[Los Angeles Magazine]]'' ranked NHHS 14th in [[Los Angeles County]], 7th of all public schools in the county, 4th of all LAUSD schools, and 1st in District 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lamag.com/best-high-schools/75-los-angeles-county-high-schools-public-private-bring-best-students/|title=75 Los Angeles County High Schools\u2014Public and Private\u2014That Bring Out the Best in Students|work=Los Angeles Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, NHHS's [[Academic Performance Index (California public schools)|Academic Performance Index]] (API) score was 778, which is 22 points below the state goal, but an improvement of 8 points since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ed-data.org/school/Los-Angeles/Los-Angeles-Unified/North-Hollywood-Senior-High|title=EdData - School Profile - North Hollywood Senior High|work=ed-data.org}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2013-14 school year, the average [[SAT Reasoning Test]] score was 1557 of a possible 2400 points.<ref name=\"dq.cde.ca.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/satactap/sat.aspx?cyear=2013-14&cchoice=SAT4b&year=1314&cdscode=19647331936350&clevel=School&ctopic=sat&level=School|title=SAT Report (CA Dept of Education)|website=Dq.cde.ca.gov}}</ref>\n \nFor the 2013-14 school year, the [[CAHSEE|California High School Exit Exam]] (CAHSEE) classified 84% of 10th graders in English and 83% of 10th graders in Mathematics, as \"proficient or better.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ed-data.org/school/Los-Angeles/Los-Angeles-Unified/North-Hollywood-Senior-High|title=EdData - School Profile - North Hollywood Senior High|website=Ed-data.org}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2014-15 school year, in the Physical Fitness Exam for 9th graders, 89.8% of students in Abdominal Strength, 65.5% of students in Aerobic Capacity, 63.1% of students in Body Composition, 91.2% of students in Flexibility, 92.1% of students in Trunk Extension Strength, and 80.9% of students in Upper Body Strength, were considered to be in the \"Healthy Fitness Zone.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/PhysFitness/PFTDN/Summary2011.aspx?r=0&t=1&y=2014-15&c=19647331936350&n=0000|title=Physical Fitness Test Results (CA Dept of Education)|website=Dq.cde.ca.gov}}</ref>\n\n===Advanced Placement Courses===\nNHHS offers 25 [[Advanced Placement]] courses: [[AP Biology]], [[AP Calculus AB]], [[AP Calculus BC]], [[AP Chemistry]], [[AP Computer Science A]], [[AP Computer Science Principles]], [[AP English Language and Composition]], [[AP English Literature and Composition]], [[AP Environmental Science]], [[AP European History]], [[AP French Language]], [[AP Human Geography]], [[AP Macroeconomics]], [[AP Music Theory]], [[AP Physics 2]], [[AP Physics C: Electricity and Magnetism]], [[AP Physics C: Mechanics]], [[AP Psychology]], [[AP Spanish Language]], [[AP Spanish Literature]], [[AP Statistics]], [[AP Studio Art]], [[AP US Government and Politics]], [[AP US History]], and [[AP World History]].\n\nFor the 2017-18 school year, 820 students took 1,883 AP examinations, with 20% receiving a score of 1, 24% receiving a score of 2, 22% receiving a score of 3, 16% receiving a score of 4, and 18% receiving a score of 5.<ref>https://data1.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/satactap/CollegeTest?cdscode=19647331936350&CollegeTest=ap&year=2017-18</ref>\n\n== Extracurriculars ==\nThere are a wide variety of extracurricular activities offered at NHHS. While many of these activities are provided by the school, after-school partnerships exist with [[Los Angeles Valley College]] (LAVC) and L.A.C.E.R. Afterschool Programs.\n\n===Competitive Academics===\n[[File:NHHS Computer Lab.jpg|thumb|''One of the computer labs.'']]\n[[File:NHHS Library.jpg|thumb|''The library.'']]\n[[File:NHHS Woodshop.jpg|thumb|''The woodshop.'']]\nNHHS offers many highly successful teams in competitive academics:\n[[Academic Decathlon]],\n[[CyberPatriot]],\n[[DECA (organization)|DECA]],\n[[Moot Court|Duke Moot Court]],\n[[FIRST Robotics]],\n[[National FFA Organization|Future Farmers of America]],\n[[Mock Trial]],\n[[North American Computational Linguistics Open Competition|North American Computational Linguistics Open competition]],\n[[National Ocean Sciences Bowl]],\n[[Physics Olympiad]],\n[[Science Bowl]],\n[[Science Olympiad]], and\n[[Debate|Speech and Debate]].\n\n===Athletics===\n[[File:NHHS Boys' Gym.jpg|thumb|''The Boys' Gym.'']]\nThe NHHS Huskies compete in the [[CIF Los Angeles City Section]]'s East Valley League. NHHS's rivals are [[Polytechnic High School (Los Angeles)|Polytechnic High School]] and [[Grant High School (Los Angeles)|Ulysses S. Grant High School]]. The NHHS Athletics Department offers:\n[[Archery]],\n[[Baseball]],\n[[Basketball]] (boys' and girls'),\n[[Cheerleading]],\n[[Cross country running|Cross Country]],\n[[American football|Football]],\n[[Golf]],\n[[Soccer]] (boys' and girls'),\n[[Softball]] (girls'),\n[[Students Run LA]],\n[[Tennis]],\n[[Track & Field]],\n[[Ultimate Frisbee]],\n[[Volleyball]] (boys' and girls'), and\n[[Weight Training]].\n\n===Performing Arts===\n[[File:NHHS Instrumental Music Room.jpg|thumb|''The instrumental music room.'']]\n[[File:NHHS Auditorium.jpg|thumb|''The auditorium.'']]\nNHHS offers a wide variety of performing arts courses.\n\n*[[Marching Band]] - During the Fall semester, the marching band is typically a Division 2A, 70-member ensemble called the ''Royal Regiment''. The band performs as a [[pep band]] at football games and competes in field tournaments.\n*[[Concert Band]] - During the Spring semester, the marching band becomes a concert band that performs at festivals, the annual Spring Concert, and various school events.\n*[[String Orchestra]] - During the Fall semester, the string orchestra prepares and performs for the annual Winter Concert.\n*[[Symphony Orchestra|Advanced Symphony Orchestra]] - During the Spring semester, the string orchestra becomes a symphony orchestra, inviting the Concert Band's top wind and percussion musicians to round out the ensemble. The orchestra performs at festivals and the annual Spring Concert.\n*[[Percussion Ensemble]] - During the Fall semester, the percussion ensemble prepares and performs for the annual Winter Concert.\n*[[Indoor percussion ensemble|Indoor Drumline]] - During the Spring semester, the indoor drumline performs in drumline tournaments, the annual Spring Percussion Concert, and various school events. \n*[[Jazz Band|Advanced Jazz Band]] - Meeting before school during both semesters, the jazz band is an approximately 20-member ensemble that performs in festivals, the annual Winter Concert, the annual Spring Concert, and various events.\n*[[Guitar|Beginning Guitar]] - During both semesters, beginning guitars is an introductory-level class for students with interest in guitar.\n*[[Choir|Vocal Ensemble]] - During both semesters, the vocal ensemble is the most advanced group that prepares and performs for festivals, the annual Winter Concert, and the annual Spring Concert.\n*[[Choir|Chorus]] - During both semesters, the chorus prepares and performs for the annual Winter Concert and the annual Spring Concert.\n*[[Choir|Beginning Choir]] - During both semesters, the beginning choir is an introductory-level class for students with no musical background.\n*[[Color guard (flag spinning)|Color Guard]] - During the Fall semester, the color guard teams up with the marching band to perform at football games and compete in field tournaments.\n*[[Dance Team]] - During the Spring semester, the colorguard becomes a dance team that performs in competitions and the annual Spring Dance Show.\n\n==Demographics==\nFor the 2018-19 school year, NHHS had a total enrollment of 2,522 students, broken down into 29.9% freshmen, 25.8% sophomores, 21.6% juniors, and 22.7% seniors. 9.6% of NHHS students were English Learners.<ref>https://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/dqcensus/EnrEthGrd.aspx?cds=19647331936350&agglevel=school&year=2018-19</ref>\n\nDuring the 2014-15 school year, the [[student-teacher ratio]] was 24 to 1, and NHHS had 11 administrators, 114 teachers, and 10 pupil services workers. Of the 114 teachers, 1 has a [[Doctorate]], 61 have [[Master's degrees]], 48 have [[Bachelor's degrees]], and 4 were unreported.<ref>[http://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/Staff/StaffEduLvl.aspx?cSelect=North^Hollywood^Seni--Los^Angeles^Uni--1964733-1936350&cYear=2014-15&cChoice=SchEduc&cType=T&cGender=B&cLevel=School&cTopic=Paif&myTimeFrame=S] {{dead link|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n{|border = \"1\" style = \"text-align: left; border-collapse: collapse; width:25%\"\n! Ethnicity !! Students (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/dqcensus/EnrEthLevels.aspx?cds=19647331936350&agglevel=School&year=2017-18|title=Enrollment by Ethnicity - North Hollywood Senior High School (CA Dept of Education)|website=Dq.cde.ca.gov}}</ref>!! Teachers (2018)<ref>https://dq.cde.ca.gov/dataquest/Staff/StaffByEth.aspx?cSelect=North^Hollywood^Seni--Los^Angeles^Uni--1964733-1936350&cYear=2017-18&cChoice=SchTeach&cType=T&cGender=B&cLevel=School&cTopic=Paif&myTimeFrame=S</ref> \n|-\n| Hispanic or Latino || 69.7% || 27.2%\n|-\n| White || 15.6% || 57.9%\n|-\n| Asian || 7.8% || 3.5%\n|-\n| Black or African American || 3.6% || 5.2%\n|-\n| Filipino || 1.9% || 2.6%\n|-\n| American Indian or Alaska Native || 0.3% || 0.8%\n|- \n| Pacific Islander || 0.2% || 0.8%\n|-\n| Other/Not Reported || 1.0% || 1.7%\n|}\n\n==Achievements==\n*At the California [[Academic Decathlon]], NHHS won 8th place in 2001, 4th place in 2002, 7th place in 2005, 9th place in 2006, 4th place in 2007, 5th place in 2008, 3rd place in 2009, 45th place in 2013, 46th place in 2014, 31st place in 2015, 51st place in 2016, 8th place in Division 3 in 2017, and 12th place in Division 2 in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academicdecathlon.org/scores.htm|title=California Academic Decathlon Website|website=Academicdecathlon.org}}</ref>\n*At the Regional [[Science Bowl]], NHHS has won 1st place every year since 1998, missing only 2005 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/North-Hollywood-High-School-LADWP-Science-Bowl--369559891.html|title=North Hollywood High School Wins Science Bowl|website=Nbclosangeles.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-north-hollywood-science-20170226-story.html|title=North Hollywood High School wins LADWP Science Bowl|first=Brittny|last=Mejia|date=26 February 2017|website=Latimes.com}}</ref> At the National [[Science Bowl]], NHHS won 1st place in 2001,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2001/may/08/local/me-60825 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Massie | last=Ritsch | title=North Hollywood High Wins U.S. Science Bowl | date=2001-05-08}}</ref> 2nd place in 2006, 6th place in 2008, 10th place in 2009, 3rd place in 2010, 2nd place in 2012, 7th place in 2013, 5th place in 2016, 9th place in 2017, and 2nd place in 2018.\n*At the [[National Ocean Sciences Bowl]]'s Los Angeles Surf Bowl, NHHS won 3rd place in 2012.\n*At the [[CSU Long Beach]] Math Day at the Beach, NHHS won 1st place in 2006, 2nd place in 2012, 5th place in 2013, and 4th place in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/beach-609065-high-competition.html|title=Troy, University high schools top math competition|date=10 April 2014|website=Ocregister.com}}</ref>\n*At the Regional [[Mandelbrot Competition]], NHHS ranked 42nd place in 2011 and 39th place in 2012. At the National [[Mandelbrot Competition]], NHHS ranked 50th place in 2011 and 73rd place in 2012.\n*At the Regional [[FIRST Robotics Competition]], NHHS's NohoRobo Team was a quarterfinalist and received the Rookie Inspiration Award in 2010, and was a 6th seed (of 66) semifinalist in 2015.\n*At the International [[Botball]] Competition, NHHS received the Outstanding Programming award and the Judges' Choice award in 2011. At the Greater Los Angeles Regional Botball Tournament, NHHS won 2nd place overall in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.botball.org/gla/2017/results|title=2017 Greater Los Angeles Regional Botball\u00ae Tournament Results - Botball\u00ae Educational Robotics Program|website=Botball.org}}</ref>\n*At the Duke [[Moot Court]] National Tournament, NHHS has won 1st place in 2009, 1st and 2nd place in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sites.duke.edu/dukemootcourt/high-school-tournament/previous-high-school-tournaments/|title=Previous Tournaments and Cases - Duke Moot Court|website=Sites.duke.edu}}</ref> was a semifinalist in 2012 and won 2nd place in 2016.\n*At the [http://www.crf-usa.org/ Constitutional Rights Foundation]'s Mock Trial State Competition, NHHS won 1st place in 1982 and 2nd place in 1983.\n*At the [[National Speech and Debate Association]]'s district qualifier, NHHS's [[speech and debate]] team won sweepstakes in [[Congressional Debate]] in 2014. In three of [[California High School Speech Association]]'s Tri-County Forensics League competitions, NHHS's team took sweepstakes in 2014. At the CHSSA's state championships, NHHS students won 10th and 11th in Congressional Debate.\n*At the National [[National Academic Quiz Tournaments|NAQT]] Tournament, NHHS won 43rd in 2009, 21st in 2012, and 33rd in 2013.\n*At the [[CyberPatriot]] National Finals, NHHS won 4th and 6th place in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhhs.net/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=288879&id=0 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224034507/http://www.nhhs.net/apps/news/show_news.jsp?REC_ID=288879&id=0 |archivedate=2014-02-24 }} </ref> 1st place in 2014,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.latimes.com/2014/mar/31/local/la-me-ln-north-hollywood-high-wins-cyber-security-20140331 | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Alicia | last=Banks | title=North Hollywood High wins national cyber-security competition | date=2014-03-31}}</ref> and 2nd and 5th place in 2015. At the California Cyber Innovation Challenge, NHHS won 1st place in 2016 and 2017.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160921210235/http://www.techwire.net/innovation/high-school-teams-compete-in-go-biz-cyber-innovation-challenge.html] </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://calpolynews.calpoly.edu/news_releases/2017/07/cyber|title=North Hollywood High School Wins California Cyber Innovation Challenge Competition at Cal Poly - Cal Poly News - Cal Poly, San Luis Obispo|website=Calpolynews.calpoly.edu}}</ref> In 2017, three teams were sent to the national finals and one team won 1st place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-edu-north-hollywood-computers-champs-20170408-story.html|title=North Hollywood High team wins national cybersecurity competition|first=Howard|last=Blume|date=8 April 2017|website=Latimes.com}}</ref>. In 2018, three teams were sent to the national finals and won 1st, 2nd, and 9th place. In 2019, NHHS won 2nd place in the Open Class Division.\n*The NHHS [[National FFA Organization|FFA]] chapter was ranked a \"Superior Chapter\" by the California FFA Association in 1951, 1953, 1954, 1957, 1958, 1959, 1960, 1963, 1967, 1980, 1989, and 1990. At the Los Angeles [[National FFA Organization|FFA]] Horticulture Contest, NHHS teams won 1st place in both Advanced Horticulture and Floral Horticulture in 2015.\n*At the Southern California [[DECA (organization)|DECA]] Conference, NHHS won 1st and 2nd place in marketing, and 1st place in business law and ethics in 2016.\n*The NHHS Baseball Team won the title of city champions in 1957 and 2012, and was a city championships runner-up in 1949, 1980, and 2011.\n*The NHHS Boys' Basketball Team won the title of city champions in 1990, and was a city championships runner-up in 1959, 1960, 1978, 1991, 2000, and 2003.\n*The NHHS Girls' Basketball Team won the title of city champions in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/highschool/varsity-times/la-sp-vi-girls-basketball-north-hollywood-wins-its-first-city-section-title-in-division-ii-20160304-story.html|title=Girls' basketball: North Hollywood wins its first City Section title in Division II|first=Eric|last=Sondheimer|date=4 March 2016|website=Latimes.com}}</ref> and was a runner-up in 1987, 1988, and 1993.\n*The NHHS Cheerleading Team won 1st place at DREAM TEAM Championships in 2011, 2nd place at YPI's Dance-Drill-Cheer Competition in 2014 and 4th place at City CIF Cheer Championships in 2018.\n*The NHHS Varsity Football Team was undefeated and league champions in 2004 and 2007.\n*The NHHS Junior-Varsity Football Team finished 10-1 and were League Champions in the 2017 Season, with two non-consecutive 5 game winning streaks.\n*The NHHS Girls' Golf Team won the title of city champions in 2010, and won individual champions in 2008 and 2009.\n*The NHHS Boys' Tennis Team was undefeated and league champions in 2017.\n*The NHHS Girls' Tennis Team won the title of Division II city champions in 2015.\n*The NHHS Boys' Volleyball Team won the title of city champions in 2000.\n*The NHHS Girls' Soccer Team won the title of city champions of Div II in 2020. \n*At the [[LAUSD]] Band and Dance Team Championships, the NHHS Royal Regiment won 1st place in 1985, 1986, 1989, 1991, 1993, 1997, 1998, 2001, 2002, 2004, and 2018.\n*At the [[Southern California Band and Orchestra Association]] marching band circuit, the NHHS Royal Regiment was a finalist in 2004, 2005, and 2006.\n*At the [http://www.drumsacrosscalifornia.com/ Drums Across California]'s [[Indoor percussion ensemble|Indoor Drumline]] Championships, the NHHS Indoor Drumline won 5th place in 2012, 4th place in 2013, 3rd place in 2014, 2nd place in 2015, 1st place in 2016, 2nd place in 2017, 1st place in 2018, and 1st place in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.drumsacrosscalifornia.com/DAC_Hall_of_Fame_Winners.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-05-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404214034/http://drumsacrosscalifornia.com/DAC_Hall_of_Fame_Winners.html |archivedate=2016-04-04 }} </ref>\n*At the [[LAUSD]] Drumline Championships, the NHHS [[Indoor percussion ensemble|Indoor Drumline]] won 2nd place in 2012, 2nd place in 2013, and 4th place in 2014.\n*In 2011, Mr. Randall Delling was named California Secondary Principal of the Year by the Association of California School Administrators.<ref>https://www.huffingtonpost.com/laura-sturza/north-hollywood-high-washington-post_b_952735.html</ref> In 2014, Mr. Jay Gehringer was named LAUSD Teacher of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laschoolreport.com/lausd-honors-22-educators-teacher-year/|title=LAUSD honors 22 educators as 'Teachers of the Year' - LA School Report|website=Laschoolreport.com}}</ref> In 2015, Mr. Altair Maine was named LAUSD Teacher of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.lausd.net/apps/news/article/470518|title=LAUSD Salutes 22 Educators as 'Teachers of the Year'|website=Home.lausd.net}}</ref> In 2016, Ms. Carrie Schwartz was named Secondary Co-Administrator of the Year by the Association of California School Administrators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acsa.org/About-Us/awards-program|title=ACSA Awards Program|website=Acsa.org}}</ref> In 2018, alum Ms. Dorothy Williams-Kohlmeyer was named LAUSD Rookie of the Year.<ref>http://csunshinetoday.csun.edu/arts-and-culture/alumna-dance-teacher-wins-rookie-teacher-of-the-year-award</ref>\n*As of 2018, NHHS has a graduation rate of 92.3%<ref>https://www.caschooldashboard.org/reports/19647331936350/2018#graduation-rate-card</ref>.\n\n==Filming location==\nNHHS has been the filming location for movies, television shows, and other productions, including the following:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/search/title|title=IMDb: Most Popular Titles With Location Matching \"North Hollywood High School - 5231 Colfax Avenue, North Hollywood, Los Angeles, California, USA\"|website=IMDb.com}}</ref>\n\n*[[The Human Comedy (film)|The Human Comedy]] (1943)\n*[[The Rockford Files]] (1974-1980)\n*[[The White Shadow (TV series)|The White Shadow]] (1978-1981)\n*[[Demolition High]] (1996)\n*[[Joan of Arcadia]] (2003-2005)\n*The Lockhavens (2009)\n*The Tudor Tutor (2010)\n*[[Shameless (American TV series)|Shameless]] Season 4, Episode 9 \"The Legend of Bonnie and Carl\" (2014)\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{refimprove section|date=November 2015}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[DJ Khalil|Khalil Abdul-Rahman]], music producer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/01/sports/la-sp-0701-crowe-20100701|title=NBA free agency might end up as boring rerun|first=Jerry|last=Crowe|date=1 July 2010|website=Articles.latimes.com}}</ref>\n*[[Larry Agran]], politician, U.S. Presidential candidate\n*[[Harry Anderson]], actor<ref>https://news.avclub.com/r-i-p-harry-anderson-actor-magician-and-star-of-nig-1825307688</ref>\n*[[Tony Angell]], artist, author\n*[[Brian Baima]], American football player\n*[[Noah Beery, Jr.]], actor\n*[[Stuart Benjamin]], film producer\n*[[Richard Beymer]], actor\n*[[Mayim Bialik]], actress\n*[[DJ Bonebrake|Donald \"D.J.\" Bonebrake]], musician\n*[[Perry Botkin Jr.]], musician, composer, producer\n*[[Ron Brand]], former Major League baseball player\n*[[Michael Broggie]], author, historian\n*[[Barbara S. Brogliatti|Barbara Brogliatti]], public relations, marketing executive\n*[[Bill Cable]], actor, model\n*[[Christy Canyon]], actress\n*[[Cindy Carol]], actress\n*[[Adam Carolla]], comedian\n*[[Nick Cassavetes]], direc